CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved In regards to the privately owned garages that offer discounted prices to residents in the area: the City of Boston and the garages try to accommodate residents as best as they can while the garages to run their business at the same time. Each garage offers a certain amount of parking spots to the city. Once those spots are filled  the garages have the right to do as they please. The city cannot intervene with their day to day operations.  If the garage informs the city that they are at capacity  then we have to take them for their word.     The city of Boston apologizes for any inconvenience that this may have caused. If you would like to discuss it further  please contact Tracey Ganiatsos via email: tracey.ganiatsos@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved In regards to the privately owned garages that offer discounted prices to residents in the area: the City of Boston and the garages try to accommodate residents as best as they can while the garages to run their business at the same time. Each garage offers a certain amount of parking spots to the city. Once those spots are filled  the garages have the right to do as they please. The city cannot intervene with their day to day operations.  If the garage informs the city that they are at capacity  then we have to take them for their word.     The city of Boston apologizes for any inconvenience that this may have caused. If you would like to discuss it further  please contact Tracey Ganiatsos via email: tracey.ganiatsos@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved In regards to the privately owned garages that offer discounted prices to residents in the area: the City of Boston and the garages try to accommodate residents as best as they can while the garages to run their business at the same time. Each garage offers a certain amount of parking spots to the city. Once those spots are filled  the garages have the right to do as they please. The city cannot intervene with their day to day operations.  If the garage informs the city that they are at capacity  then we have to take them for their word.     The city of Boston apologizes for any inconvenience that this may have caused. If you would like to discuss it further  please contact Tracey Ganiatsos via email: tracey.ganiatsos@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The Boston Transportation Department is currently looking at every two way street in every neighborhood that may be affected by snow. We are working with the Public Works Department snow removal team to help with this process.  We are also working with the Boston Police Department and other first responding agencies that may have any feedback pertaining to this matter.  The City of Boston is doing everything they can to help residents and visitors traveling through our streets safely and efficiently this winter and for any severe weather in the future that may impede safe travel.  If you have any questions  please do not hesitate to contact me.  Kevin Donahue  Director of Community Affairs  Boston Transportation Department  617-635-2447  Kevin.donahue@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved In regards to the privately owned garages that offer discounted prices to residents in the area: the City of Boston and the garages try to accommodate residents as best as they can while the garages to run their business at the same time. Each garage offers a certain amount of parking spots to the city. Once those spots are filled  the garages have the right to do as they please. The city cannot intervene with their day to day operations.  If the garage informs the city that they are at capacity  then we have to take them for their word.     The city of Boston apologizes for any inconvenience that this may have caused. If you would like to discuss it further  please contact Tracey Ganiatsos via email: tracey.ganiatsos@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved In regards to the privately owned garages that offer discounted prices to residents in the area: the City of Boston and the garages try to accommodate residents as best as they can while the garages to run their business at the same time. Each garage offers a certain amount of parking spots to the city. Once those spots are filled  the garages have the right to do as they please. The city cannot intervene with their day to day operations.  If the garage informs the city that they are at capacity  then we have to take them for their word.     The city of Boston apologizes for any inconvenience that this may have caused. If you would like to discuss it further  please contact Tracey Ganiatsos via email: tracey.ganiatsos@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The Boston Transportation Department is currently looking at every two way street in every neighborhood that may be affected by snow. We are working with the Public Works Department snow removal team to help with this process.  We are also working with the Boston Police Department and other first responding agencies that may have any feedback pertaining to this matter.  The City of Boston is doing everything they can to help residents and visitors traveling through our streets safely and efficiently this winter and for any severe weather in the future that may impede safe travel.  If you have any questions  please do not hesitate to contact me.  Kevin Donahue  Director of Community Affairs  Boston Transportation Department  617-635-2447  Kevin.donahue@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved In regards to the privately owned garages that offer discounted prices to residents in the area: the City of Boston and the garages try to accommodate residents as best as they can while the garages to run their business at the same time. Each garage offers a certain amount of parking spots to the city. Once those spots are filled  the garages have the right to do as they please. The city cannot intervene with their day to day operations.  If the garage informs the city that they are at capacity  then we have to take them for their word.     The city of Boston apologizes for any inconvenience that this may have caused. If you would like to discuss it further  please contact Tracey Ganiatsos via email: tracey.ganiatsos@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved In regards to the privately owned garages that offer discounted prices to residents in the area: the City of Boston and the garages try to accommodate residents as best as they can while the garages to run their business at the same time. Each garage offers a certain amount of parking spots to the city. Once those spots are filled  the garages have the right to do as they please. The city cannot intervene with their day to day operations.  If the garage informs the city that they are at capacity  then we have to take them for their word.     The city of Boston apologizes for any inconvenience that this may have caused. If you would like to discuss it further  please contact Tracey Ganiatsos via email: tracey.ganiatsos@boston.gov

We are also working with the Boston Police Department and other first responding agencies that may have any feedback pertaining to this matter. CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The Boston Transportation Department is currently looking at every two way street in every neighborhood that may be affected by snow. We are working with the Public Works Department snow removal team to help with this process.  We are also working with the Boston Police Department and other first responding agencies that may have any feedback pertaining to this matter.  The City of Boston is doing everything they can to help residents and visitors traveling through our streets safely and efficiently this winter and for any severe weather in the future that may impede safe travel.  If you have any questions  please do not hesitate to contact me.  Kevin Donahue  Director of Community Affairs  Boston Transportation Department  617-635-2447  Kevin.donahue@boston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The Boston Transportation Department is currently looking at every converted two way street in South Boston. We are working with the Public Works Department as well as the Boston Police Department and other first responding agencies that may have any helpful input pertaining to this matter. This is not an easy task to quickly decide if the One Ways will work during the off season as they did during the winter. As I am sure you understand  this is a very delicate decision  which has a lot of moving parts that deserves a lot of attention.     The City of Boston appreciates your feedback and your interest in this matter as well. As a resident  your input is a vital piece of information which helps with the decision.     The City of Boston is doing everything they can to accommodate the needs/wants of the residents as well as its visitors traveling through our streets safely and efficiently.    We are confident that a decision will be made on this issue relatively soon.    If you have any questions  please do not hesitate to contact me.    Kevin Donahue  Director of Community Affairs   Boston Transportation Department  kevin.donahue@boston.gov  617-635-2447

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The Boston Transportation Department is currently looking at every converted two way street in South Boston. We are working with the Public Works Department as well as the Boston Police Department and other first responding agencies that may have any helpful input pertaining to this matter. This is not an easy task to quickly decide if the One Ways will work during the off season as they did during the winter. As I am sure you understand  this is a very delicate decision  which has a lot of moving parts that deserves a lot of attention.     The City of Boston appreciates your feedback and your interest in this matter as well. As a resident  your input is a vital piece of information which helps with the decision.     The City of Boston is doing everything they can to accommodate the needs/wants of the residents as well as its visitors traveling through our streets safely and efficiently.    We are confident that a decision will be made on this issue relatively soon.    If you have any questions  please do not hesitate to contact me.    Kevin Donahue  Director of Community Affairs   Boston Transportation Department  kevin.donahue@boston.gov  617-635-2447

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Noted Hi Kim  I met with Ms. Keough and Mr. Ostiguy earlier in the week on multiple occasions to address their concerns. I met with Mr. Ostiguy again this morning to hear from his children. During the course of our investigation  there were students who mistreated the Ostiguy children. We have addressed those students. It also came to light that the children continue to leave their assigned seats and the issues tend to arise after they move to the back of the bus. In response to this  Dr. Sealy and I have assigned every student a new seat on the bus and have instructed the driver to specifically report any student who moves from their assigned seat.  I've also addressed personally every student on the bus.  I'm happy to talk more if you need addition information. THanks and have a great weekend. Best  Robby

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2015-09-02 12:54:13.387 Case Noted Thank you for bringing this matter to our attention.    In order to help us better understand your request for a barrier; please visit the link below to download a request form to provide some background information on your request. Upon receipt of the completed form  engineering staff will review the form and any supporting documentation and perform a site visit for a safety evaluation. Based on the information provided and the site evaluation  we will determine what safety measures (if any) can be implemented in response to your request.     Please note that the completion of this form does not guarantee a barrier will be installed. Other safety measures such as signage  lighting  and/or changes to roadway geometry may also be implemented to address safety concerns instead of  or in addition to  your request for a barrier.    If you have any questions  please contact the Public Works Department Engineering Division at 617-635-4968 or at pwdengineering@boston.gov.  Again  we appreciate and thank you for your interest in public safety and the welfare of your community.    Barrier Request Form:  https://attachments.cityofboston.gov/?f=14990&fid=28a944f9

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved The Boston Transportation Department is currently looking at every converted two way street in South Boston. We are working with the Public Works Department as well as the Boston Police Department and other first responding agencies that may have any helpful input pertaining to this matter. This is not an easy task to quickly decide if the One Ways will work during the off season as they did during the winter. As I am sure you understand  this is a very delicate decision  which has a lot of moving parts that deserves a lot of attention.     The City of Boston appreciates your feedback and your interest in this matter as well. As a resident  your input is a vital piece of information which helps with the decision.     The City of Boston is doing everything they can to accommodate the needs/wants of the residents as well as its visitors traveling through our streets safely and efficiently.    We are confident that a decision will be made on this issue relatively soon.    If you have any questions  please do not hesitate to contact me.    Kevin Donahue  Director of Community Affairs   Boston Transportation Department  kevin.donahue@boston.gov  617-635-2447

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Resolved Please allow this email to serve as the Boston Public Library's response to Service Request no. 101001363099.  The Boston Public Library (BPL) does require contact information to establish an account for every library user.  This personal information remains confidential and can only be viewed online by the patron when that patron has logged into the BPL online catalog by entering the patron's library card number and personally selected 4-digit PIN.  The BPL encourages patrons to keep their library card number and PIN private  just as one would a credit or debit card.  The personal information is only able to be displayed when a patron is logged in to the online catalog; it is not stored by the third party vendor who hosts the BPL catalog.  The library card number and PIN remain securely stored on the BPL's server.  Since 2011  the BPL has contacted with Bibliocommons  Inc. for purposes of hosting the BPL's catalog.  Bibliocommons was selected because it addressed the most frequently patron-suggested improvements to the online catalog.  Namely  Bibliocommons provides:   *         Relevancy ranking of search results  *         Reading recommendations  *         The ability to create a user name in lieu of entering the 14-digit library barcode  *         Social features like ratings  reviews  and sharing to services like Facebook and Twitter  *         The option to create reading history lists automatically as items are returned  Now  as always  the BPL does not store a patron's circulation history.  Once a borrowing transaction is complete  the record of that transaction is deleted from the BPL server.  The only things stored beyond that  in the catalog  are lists a patron chooses to make for himself or information a patron chooses to share with others  like reviews or ratings.  The use of the social features are entirely optional.  If a patron never rates or reviews a title  none of the patron's activities will ever be shared with others.  Also  please note  if a patron does not like the BPL's main catalog  an alternate catalog is offered from the "Alternate Catalog" link in the BPL Collections menu on http://bpl.org.  If you have questions or require any additional information  please let me know.  Thank you.  _____________________________________ Deborah A. Kirrane Clerk of the Board Boston Public Library 700 Boylston Street | Boston  MA 02116 o: 617.859.2370 |

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Noted I sent the following email to the MP Faculty earlier today. I did not hang flyers throughout the building because I considered the name of the play to be controversial. However  I did consider the issues covered in this play to be relevant and introduced in a way that it may have a positive affect on some our students.  I believe that the person who called the hotline did not read the message below or look at the actual flyer.  If you have any questions  contact me at any time.   Than you.    MP Family   Our students have been invited to attend an MIT showing of "Slut The Play". This is a wonderful opportunity to open up a conversation with our students about a topic that is shaming and transformative in their lives. In addition they will experience MIT and the campus at large.  I hope to empower students with knowledge and conversation around the topic and bring light to an issue that is prevalent among many school communities.   Please send students you select to the Student Center to pick up a Permission Slip.   Also  the Event is  free...there is no cost for our students or chaperons.  One Vision  One Community --  Jewel R. Perry Family & Community Engagement Coordinator Madison Park Vocational Technical High School 617-635-8970 x129  --   Director of Student Services @ Madison Park Technical Vocational High School (617) 635-8552  "Kids need to think that you care  before they care what you think." Wes Moore

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Noted  All new trees are under warranty for two years from the date they were planted. The BPRD relies heavily on business/homeowners to help water the trees and to inform the BPRD if the trees health is declining after the first two years. The contractor who planted the tree is responsible for watering the trees as well during the growing season for the first two years. All new trees are inspected every summer during the warranty period to make sure they are alive and healthy. If they are found to be dead they will be placed on the warranty replacement list for the contractor to replace. The department is also currently working on a new handout to give to residents regarding new trees. There is a door knocker that is currently being used when a site is inspected for a new tree to be planted.

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2015-05-29 08:58:49.883 Case Resolved Dear Constituent     The PWD Roadway Repair Contractor is working on your street performing patch paving.    It is an important city service for your neighborhood to provide the best permanent repairs of previous utility excavations or potholes.     The construction process is to dig out 6.5 inches of material and place 5 inches of dense binder hot mix asphalt in 2 lifts. The dense binder gives the patch its strength but is has large stones and is not conducive to providing a smooth ride  the contractor usually within a week comes back and places 1.5 inches of  the top course. The top course is hot mix asphalt  that provides the smooth ride.    The street is leafleted before the work begins where it explains that it is a mufti phase construction operation and you should look at the dates since they will change as each construction phases progresses.     Our goal is to allow parking between phases and not post the street for the entire time the work takes place. This is why the contractor repeatedly changes the dates.     We spoke to the contractor about his need to be totally accurate when posting and leafletting  for upcoming work.     Since this is a patching contract  the contractor may only be on your street for only a short period of time; giving the appearance of not showing up.     Sometimes poor weather  plant breakdowns  or equipment failure occurs which results in the delay of the upcoming work.     The CIU spoke to the contractor about his need to do a better job on changing the dates when those situations arise.     Any questions you call the City Engineer Tom Mougamian. 617-304-7308     The city apologizes for the inconvenience this necessary work has caused.     Sincerely     Mark Cardarelli  Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance  Boston Public Works Department  617-635-4951 Office

The City needs to maintain its streets and sidewalks and is working everyday to make that happen.    In addition utilities and private contractors are installing new mains/conduits  performing service connection work  maintenance upkeep  or emergency repairs.    We also have new buildings being built or existing buildings being refurbished  across the City.    The amount of construction is a sign of how vibrant the City of Boston is..    The Transportation Department takes into account traffic impact  when issuing a permit.    They take very seriously the need for construction to move as fast as possible considering the work being done.    All contractors are required to call for police details which greatly assist in the flow of traffic.    However with all the reasons stated above there may be from time to time a delay in getting around the City.     We appreciate your patience.     For any questions or concerns  please contact the number listed below    Sincerely     Mark Cardarelli  Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance  Boston Public Works
SUBJECT: Mayor's 24 Hour Hotline
TYPE: General Comments For a Program or Policy

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2015-09-15 10:34:15.737 Case Noted While this was an anonymous complaint we want to explain thatthe hours at the BCYF Curley Community Center were not meeting the needs of working professionals due to the fact the center did not open until8:00 a.m. People who started work at9 a.m.did not have sufficient time to use the facility before work  which was causing a large amount of residents to have to find other fitness facilities. After reviewing how many people use the center on average between7:30 p.m.andclosing (16) we decided to open at6:30 a.m. in hopes of serving the pre-work workout crowd.In order to accommodate the earlier opening we had to change staff schedules and this did not allow us to keep the facility open as late as we have in the past.   We do realize the inconvenience this may have caused member so we have extended the proposed closing to8:30 p.m. This is still an earlier closing than in the past but will allow us to serve more members in the morning. Sandy     Sandy Holden Public Information Manager Boston Centers for Youth & Families (BCYF)

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Noted  Thank you for your comments regarding the Hempfest  also known by its organizers as The Boston Freedom Rally.   The Boston Parks and Recreation Department has legally challenged on multiple occasions dating back to the 1990s.  The courts have allowed the event to continue despite our concerns over illicit drug use  damage to park property  and amplified music.  We must respect these court decisions and the First Amendment rights of the participants.   For those who have suggested that the event be moved to another park location  please note that the organizers specifically request that the event be held on Boston Common and we have no say in that part of their application.   We will continue to work with the City of Boston Law Department to discuss our options moving forward.  Your support and input is invaluable to this process.  We are currently collecting written comments that we will present as discussions of this matter move forward.   Please understand that we are constrained by past legal decisions interpreting this as an event protected by free speech but we will continue to work to mitigate impacts on the Common and the community as best we can.   Chris Cook Commissioner

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2016-01-06 13:51:03.93 Case Noted "Thank you for your interest in "Drive Boston."    As you may know  owning a car is an expensive proposition and one that is out of reach for some people.  By locating vehicles in neighborhoods that have not previously been served by traditional car share programs  Drive Boston provides residents with easy access to motor vehicles on those occasions when traveling by car would come in handy.    At the same time  on-street parking in the City can be difficult as a result of too many vehicles competing for parking at a limited amount of curb-space.  The Drive Boston program will free up parking spaces on Boston's streets by encouraging residents to make the decision to share a car rather than purchase their own.   Each individual who makes this decision will also be helping to improve the environment by decreasing overall emissions from motor vehicles.    Mayor Walsh is supportive of the Boston Transportation Department's efforts to implement Drive Boston and other initiatives designed to improve travel conditions on Boston's local streets for drivers  cyclists and pedestrians  alleviate the parking crunch  and provide equity to transportation for all City residents.    I hope that this answers your questions.  Please feel free to contact us with any further transportation related issues that you may have.

TYPE: General Comments For a Program or Policy

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2015-11-09 15:31:20.84 Case Noted The City of Boston has partnered with Zipcar and Enterprise CarShare to bring 80 new car-share vehicles to Boston through the DriveBoston program. Planners from the Transportation Department visited a range of locations and selected places with the largest benefit for residents that had the smallest impact on street operations and parking. The program will place vehicles in dedicated spaces around the City  including many that are currently underserved by car-share options. The majority of the spaces will be in City-owned municipal parking lots (49 spaces)  with the remaining 31 spots being placed on street corners. The location of spaces were chosen by examining car registrations per household  average household mileage per day  the proximity to MBTA stations as well as Hubway stations  Main Street districts and coordination with Zipcar and Enterprise CarShare. Roxbury received 12 spots and Dorchester received 10 spots. Jamaica Plain received eight spots and the additional spots were distributed in small numbers across the City. The program spaces are all visible on an online map at boston.gov/driveboston.     The DriveBoston program has three main goals: (1) create "mobility hubs" at key MBTA stations and along bus routes to strengthen the City's transportation network; (2) reduce the number of private vehicles per household which should relieve parking pressure; and (3) better connect the Main Street Business Districts. Data collected about how frequently people use the vehicles and for what purposes will help inform the City's transportation planners on the success of the program.    National studies on the impact of car-share programs have shown significant  positive impacts.  Expanding car-share in a city  for example  can help reduce local greenhouse gas emissions. Moreover  increasing car-share availability has been shown to reduce local car ownership  as residents chose to join a car-share program rather than buy  maintain and find parking for one. One study estimates that adding each car-share vehicles reduces between nine and 13 cars overall.      The DriveBoston program is an early action initiative of Go Boston 2030  the City's transportation planning effort. The effort is being led by the Boston Transportation Department and the Mayor's Mobility Plan Advisory Committee. One of the primary goals that emerged from the GoBoston2030 planning process so far  which involved over 6 000 people  was to provide better access to all modes of travel. This call for access to all kinds of ways to get around the city has led to an aspirational target of having every Boston household within a 10 minute walk of a rail station or key bus route  a Hubway station  and car-share.    During this 18 month pilot program  The City of Boston will work with Zipcar and Enterprise CarShare to collect data on usage and survey information from members. The City will analyze the data and use it to inform constituents on the future of the program.

TYPE: General Comments For a Program or Policy

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2016-01-06 15:53:21.183 Case Noted "Thank you for your interest in "Drive Boston."    As you may know  owning a car is an expensive proposition and one that is out of reach for some people.  By locating vehicles in neighborhoods that have not previously been served by traditional car share programs  Drive Boston provides residents with easy access to motor vehicles on those occasions when traveling by car would come in handy.    At the same time  on-street parking in the City can be difficult as a result of too many vehicles competing for parking at a limited amount of curb-space.  The Drive Boston program will free up parking spaces on Boston's streets by encouraging residents to make the decision to share a car rather than purchase their own.   Each individual who makes this decision will also be helping to improve the environment by decreasing overall emissions from motor vehicles.    Mayor Walsh is supportive of the Boston Transportation Department's efforts to implement Drive Boston and other initiatives designed to improve travel conditions on Boston's local streets for drivers  cyclists and pedestrians  alleviate the parking crunch  and provide equity to transportation for all City residents.    I hope that this answers your questions.  Please feel free to contact us with any further transportation related issues that you may have.

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2016-01-06 14:09:56.18 Case Noted "Thank you for your interest in "Drive Boston."    As you may know  owning a car is an expensive proposition and one that is out of reach for some people.  By locating vehicles in neighborhoods that have not previously been served by traditional car share programs  Drive Boston provides residents with easy access to motor vehicles on those occasions when traveling by car would come in handy.    At the same time  on-street parking in the City can be difficult as a result of too many vehicles competing for parking at a limited amount of curb-space.  The Drive Boston program will free up parking spaces on Boston's streets by encouraging residents to make the decision to share a car rather than purchase their own.   Each individual who makes this decision will also be helping to improve the environment by decreasing overall emissions from motor vehicles.    Mayor Walsh is supportive of the Boston Transportation Department's efforts to implement Drive Boston and other initiatives designed to improve travel conditions on Boston's local streets for drivers  cyclists and pedestrians  alleviate the parking crunch  and provide equity to transportation for all City residents.    I hope that this answers your questions.  Please feel free to contact us with any further transportation related issues that you may have.

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2016-01-06 12:40:31.87 Case Noted The Boston Transportation does its best to maintain a steady flow of traffic throughout the day and evening. We make adjustments to signal timing when applicable to help improve traffic flow. We also alert the Boston Police and/or the Massachusetts State Police of when there may be an irregular flow of traffic. We are able to view certain areas of the City through a live feed from cameras to our Traffic Management Center; which allows us to make adjustments to the signal timing. We do not however have the authority or the capability to make signal adjustments to traffic signals owned by other authorities.   The City of Boston and the Transportation Department apologize for any inconvenience the traffic congestion has caused you.  If you have any questions or concerns  or would like to discuss this issue further  please do not hesitate to contact the Boston Transportation Department @ btd@cityofboston.gov

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2016-01-06 13:17:08.457 Case Noted The Boston Transportation Department does its best to accommodate the needs of constituents. We understand that parking is at a premium and that there are times where a person may need to stop for a second at open curb space. There are times where we will not issue a ticket and ask the driver to please move. If the vehicle is unattended and it poses a safety concern  a ticket will be issued.  Questions concerning violations can be answered over the phone by calling the Office of the Parking Clerk at (617) 635-4410. When requesting an appeal  the individual should be sure to indicate the nature of the dispute and include his/her name  mailing address  the plate registration and the ticket number(s) to be disputed. There are three ways to request an appeal of a parking violation: In Person  Office of the Parking Clerk  Room 224  1 City Hall Plaza  Boston  MA 02201  Mon-Fri: 9:00am - 4:30pm  By Mail  Send a written request to: City of Boston  P.O. Box 55800  Boston  MA 02205 or Online @ cityofboston.gov.  Late fees will be added after 21 days from the date of issue.  The City of Boston apologizes for the inconvenience.
SUBJECT: Mayor's 24 Hour Hotline
TYPE: General Comments For a Program or Policy
